    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-12-16T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-12-16T03:00:00-05:00" n="1071"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1071">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/12–1645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Myers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Teintsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-16T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 16, 1945—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 17—12:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>30. [To Embassy:] War Transportation Board removed from Frazar premises 97 cases
                    motor car parts, 96 tires, 20 batteries and 153 tins on [<hi rend="italic"
                        >of</hi>] carbide on December 14 (Embassy’s 2137 of December 11, 10 a.m. and
                    my telegram No. 28, December 14, 4 p.m.), notwithstanding Consulate General’s
                    prior request to cease removals and return goods already removed.</p>
                <p>Stevens,<note n="62" xml:id="d1071fn62">Harry E. Stevens, Second Secretary of
                        Embassy in China and Consul on detail to Peiping.</note> Peiping, informed
                    in memorandum dated December 12 from Generalissimo’s Headquarters, Peiping, that
                    Yorkson Shen had requested General Li Tsung-jen to order General Chiang Shih-yi
                    to stop “disturbing the goods of the Karagheusian Wool Company”, which order has
                    been issued.</p>
                <p>Sent to Embassy, repeated to Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Myers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
